00:49:28.947 --> 00:49:30.280
and you know what's interesting?

00:49:30.280 --> 00:49:35.270
This shows you why anybody
pretends to predict the market

00:49:35.270 --> 00:49:37.520
except on a long-term basis.

00:49:37.520 --> 00:49:41.360
Incredibly, Eisenhower
left office in '62.

00:49:41.360 --> 00:49:44.090
Do you know the price-earning
ratio of the Dow

00:49:44.090 --> 00:49:48.530
steadily went down from
22 times earnings-- not

00:49:48.530 --> 00:49:52.620
all at once-- to a
low of six times years

00:49:52.620 --> 00:49:55.120
later when Carter
became president?

00:49:55.120 --> 00:50:00.840
And then it went back up
and reached a new high

00:50:00.840 --> 00:50:02.390
during the past 50 years.

00:50:02.390 --> 00:50:07.050
It hit about 23 times
earnings under Clinton.

00:50:07.050 --> 00:50:10.210
And earnings are
defined by "Value Line"

00:50:10.210 --> 00:50:11.450
as operating earnings.

00:50:11.450 --> 00:50:18.500
Operating earnings, you leave
out non-recurring earnings.

00:50:18.500 --> 00:50:21.180
They usually leave
out or write off,

00:50:21.180 --> 00:50:25.639
so they have their own what I
call the best way of analyzing

00:50:25.639 --> 00:50:26.430
operating earnings.

00:50:26.430 --> 00:50:29.220
So I'll be talking about
operating earnings now.

00:50:29.220 --> 00:50:32.777
SPEAKER: How do you know what's
a good brand ahead of time?

00:50:32.777 --> 00:50:33.860
THORNTON L. O'GLOVE: Yeah.

00:50:33.860 --> 00:50:38.820
The question is there are so
many offerings that go public.

00:50:38.820 --> 00:50:42.450
Obviously if you read David
Aaker's book, at least

00:50:42.450 --> 00:50:44.560
all these companies
are successful.

00:50:44.560 --> 00:50:47.590
He doesn't name the thousands
that have gone public

00:50:47.590 --> 00:50:48.990
over the years.

00:50:48.990 --> 00:50:51.280
Especially during
the dot com boom,

00:50:51.280 --> 00:50:56.120
there was really-- you want
to talk about psychology,

00:50:56.120 --> 00:50:58.400
most of these companies
went public and some of them

00:50:58.400 --> 00:51:01.470
went up from $10 to
hundreds and hundreds.

00:51:01.470 --> 00:51:03.900
They had no earnings
even to support them.

00:51:03.900 --> 00:51:07.450
And today there's a lot of
these price-earning ratio--

00:51:07.450 --> 00:51:10.270
these new offerings around
have very little in earnings

00:51:10.270 --> 00:51:11.245
to support them.

00:51:11.245 --> 00:51:14.100
So that's a great question.

00:51:14.100 --> 00:51:16.910
One thing I've also looked
at is the competition.

00:51:16.910 --> 00:51:18.820
The first thing I look
at is competition.

00:51:18.820 --> 00:51:21.530
How much competition
do they have?

00:51:21.530 --> 00:51:24.090
The little the
competition they have,

00:51:24.090 --> 00:51:27.760
the more the branded name,
or what they call the moat,

00:51:27.760 --> 00:51:32.300
M-O-A-T, the moat around them,
and the more difficult it is

00:51:32.300 --> 00:51:36.620
to do what they do, then the
better off you're going to be.

00:51:36.620 --> 00:51:39.710
Some of the great examples
of all time, McDonald's.

00:51:39.710 --> 00:51:41.380
Never been a franchise.

00:51:41.380 --> 00:51:44.330
McDonald's only started
with a few franchises.

00:51:44.330 --> 00:51:46.630
And the same thing
on Burger King,

00:51:46.630 --> 00:51:51.340
and on Starbucks, Microsoft.

00:51:51.340 --> 00:51:54.610
But if you read, Microsoft,
when it first went public,

00:51:54.610 --> 00:51:58.580
it was in the forefront
of the internet.

00:51:58.580 --> 00:52:00.632
And one of the biggest
mistakes IBM made was they

00:52:00.632 --> 00:52:01.590
could have bought them.

00:52:01.590 --> 00:52:02.500
They didn't buy them.

00:52:02.500 --> 00:52:04.070
And when you read
a prospectus, he

00:52:04.070 --> 00:52:07.890
was a young guy-- sometimes
you can see genius.

00:52:07.890 --> 00:52:10.230
When you read about-- one
thing about prospectus,

00:52:10.230 --> 00:52:11.690
if you want to
read the 80 pages,

00:52:11.690 --> 00:52:14.370
it will give you
so much information

00:52:14.370 --> 00:52:19.310
that is not stilted, because
they come under SEC regulation

00:52:19.310 --> 00:52:23.380
and they can't hide the
warts and things like that.

00:52:23.380 --> 00:52:26.469
So if they have
heavy competition,

00:52:26.469 --> 00:52:28.010
or they have a
particular competitor,

00:52:28.010 --> 00:52:30.040
that has to be revealed
in the prospectus.

00:52:30.040 --> 00:52:32.081
Also you have to look at
the price-earning ratio.

00:52:32.081 --> 00:52:34.580
Remember now, in a
bull market, they're

00:52:34.580 --> 00:52:38.910
going to come out with these new
offerings that inflated values.

00:52:38.910 --> 00:52:41.340
The best time to buy a new
offering is when the market is

00:52:41.340 --> 00:52:48.053
either sideways or you
have recovered from a-- you

00:52:48.053 --> 00:52:50.260
don't have to have
a crash, but a 20--

00:52:50.260 --> 00:52:52.070
for example, a 20% decline.

00:52:52.070 --> 00:52:56.590
A bear market is loosely
declined as 20% down.

00:52:56.590 --> 00:52:59.037
A crash, 40%.

